block content
   +pageTitle

   +pod('Shared Biochemistry')
      .uk-width-medium-1-1
         p Find links to more information and ideas for extensions that support lessons in the Shared Biochemistry module.
         p <strong>GFP videos</strong>
            ul
               li
                  a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sl2PRHGpYuU") A Green Light for Biology: Making the Invisible Visible (Secrets of the Sequence video series)
               li
                  a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d-gUPSVX25U") Green Fluorescent Protein: What Is this Thing? (video)
         p <strong>Spider silk information</strong>
            ul
               li
                  a(href="https://boltthreads.com") Bolt Threads (website)
               li
                  a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=O8AyS1iZp0o") Fashion's Biotech Future (video)

               p <strong>Spider silk extension</strong>
                  ul
                     li Spiders make different kinds of silk that have different properties. Scientists have been able to learn from natural variations in spider silk proteins to make products that have different properties: stronger, softer, water-proof, etc. How do changes in the DNA sequences of spider silk genes lead to differences in the properties of spider silks?

         p <strong>More information about fireflies</strong>
            ul
               li
                  a(href="https://www.theguardian.com/books/gallery/2016/jun/08/night-workers-how-evolution-drives-the-firefly-dance-in-pictures") Images
               li
                  a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RpywSqvXDqc") Video from Science Friday
         p <strong>PDB-101 (website)</strong>
            ul
               li Includes information about
                  a(href="http://pdb101.rcsb.org/motm/78")  luciferase
                  |,
                  a(href="http://pdb101.rcsb.org/motm/14")  insulin
                  |,
                  a(href="http://pdb101.rcsb.org/motm/42")  GFP
                  |, and more.
               li
                  | Browse the
                  a(href="http://pdb101.rcsb.org/browse")  Molecules of Life category
                  |  to learn more about proteins that are shared among all living things
               li
                  | Paper models of
                  a(href="http://pdb101.rcsb.org/learn/resources/paper_models")  DNA, GFP, insulin, tRNA, and more
         p <strong>Types of Proteins extension</strong>
            ul
               li How does protein shape contribute to protein function? Have students choose an example from this activity and research the connection between the protein's shape and its function. PDB-101 (above) is a good resource for this type of information.
         p <strong>Wet Lab</strong>
            ul
               li
                  a(href="http://teach.genetics.utah.edu/content/labs/DNA_Extraction.pdf") How to Extract DNA from Anything Living
                  |  — To emphasize that all living things contain DNA, use multiple sources, such as a plant (peas), an animal (chicken liver), and a fungus (mushrooms). The more diverse the better!


   +pod('Common Ancestry')
      .uk-width-medium-1-1
         p
         strong Ancestry of cetaceans
         p There are many videos and pieces of writing about the evolution of cetaceans. A few are listed below:

         ul
            li
               | Nature news and Views article: de Muizon, C. (2001). Walking with whales.  Nature 413, 259-260. doi:10.1038/35095137
            li
               | Website of University of Michigan researcher
               a(href="http://www-personal.umich.edu/~gingeric/PDGwhales/Whales.htm" target="_blank")  Philip Gingerich
               | , who has been researching ungulate and cetacean fossils for decades. Includes links to many of his publications.
            li
               | National Geographic article, August, 2010 issue (subscription required).
               a(href="http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2010/08/whale-evolution/mueller-text" target="_blank")  Valley of the Whales
               | , by Tom Mueller.
            li
               a(href="http://www.pbs.org/wgbh/evolution/library/03/4/l_034_05.html" target="_blank") PBS video
               |  (requires QuickTime 7 plugin); alternate
               a(href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I2C-3PjNGok" target="_blank")  YouTube link
            li
               | National Geographic Channel:
               a(href="https://www.youtube.com/view_play_list?p=4D391B1E172D1005" target="_blank")  Whale Evolution

         p
         strong Milk caseins
         ul
            li
               | Where does milk come from? — Scientific American
               a(href="http://blogs.scientificamerican.com/thoughtomics/where-does-milk-come-from/" target="_blank")  blog entry
               |  explaining the origins of casein genes:

         p
         strong Ancestry of pandas
         ul
            li
               a(href="http://www.livescience.com/24788-oldest-panda-fossils.html" target="_blank") LiveScience article
               |  about the Kretzoiarctos fossil (2012)
            li
               | Brian Switek's
               a(href="https://www.wired.com/2010/04/life-in-the-trees-not-bamboo-shaped-the-pandas-thumb/" target="_blank")  2010 Wired article
               |  about Ailurus fulgens, a fossil from the ancestral line of the red panda: Life in the trees, not bamboo, shaped the panda's "thumb."
            li
               | Brian Switek's
               a(href="https://www.wired.com/2011/01/bears-and-bamboo-the-fossil-record-of-giant-pandas/" target="_blank")  2011 Wired article
               |  about the fossil history of the giant panda. Bears and bamboo: the fossil record of giant pandas. Note: In the first paragraph, the article refers to "panda porn."

         p
         strong Evidence for Common Ancestry
         ul
            li
               | The interactive phylogenetic tree
               a(href="/content/selection/tracktraits/" target="_blank")  Tracking Traits Through Time
               |  explores the animal family tree.
            li
               a(href="http://www.ucmp.berkeley.edu" target="_blank") The University of California Museum of Paleontology
               |  has an searchable online
               a(href="http://www.ucmp.berkeley.edu/science/collections.php" target="_blank")  image catalog
               |  of fossilized plants, animals, and microorganisms.

         p
         strong Phylogenetic tree
         ul
            li
               a(href="http://www.timetree.org" target="_blank") Time Tree
               |  has a tool that provides information and references about time since species diverged from a common ancestor. Also available for free download is a poster of the Timetree of Life.

   +pod('Heredity')
      .uk-width-medium-1-1
         p
         strong Variation in dogs
         ul
            li
               a(href="https://vimeo.com/19472436" target="_blank") Dogs Decoded
               |  — NOVA documentary

         p
         strong Variation in pigeons
         ul
            li
               a(href="http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/pigeons/" target="_blank") Pigeon Breeding: Genetics at Work
               |  — This module includes the pigeon-breeding puzzle game Pigeonetics, and more information about specific pigeon traits, genes, and alleles.

         p
         strong Human variation
         ul
            li
               a(href="http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/basics/haplotype" target="_blank") Mutation and Haplotypes
               |  explains how mutations accumulate in our DNA, and how scientists use DNA variations to understand human ancestry.

         p Several other pages on Learn.Genetics also have information that help clarify the connection between variations in DNA and human traits, as well as a molecular view of Mendelian inheritance patterns:
         ul
            li
               a(href="http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/basics/patterns/" target="_blank") What are dominant and recessive?
            li
               a(href="http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/basics/blood/" target="_blank") Genes and Blood Type
            li
               a(href="http://learn.genetics.utah.edu/content/basics/neurofibromin/" target="_blank") Test Neurofibromin Activity in a cell

