   +pod('Speciation')
      .uk-width-medium-1-1
         p
         strong Defining 'Species'

         p Depending on what they're studying (for example, fossils, microbes, plants, or animals) biologists define species in different ways. The articles below delve into this topic a little more deeply.
         ul
            li What Is a Species? from the
               a(href='http://media.eol.org/info/468' target="_blank")  Encyclopedia of Life
            li What Is a Species? from
               a(href='https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/what-is-a-species/' target="_blank")  Scientific American
            li
               a(href="http://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/why-should-we-care-about-species-4277923" target="_blank") Why Should We Care about Species?
               |  from Scitable also explains why the definitions matter.

         p
         strong More about hawthorn and apple flies
         ul
            li
               a(href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-ever-hybrid-shark-discovered-off-australia/2012/01/03/gIQAPy00YP_story.html" target="_blank") All Hail the Apple Maggot!
               |  — a 2015 New York Times article by Olivia Judson about extinction and speciation, featuring apple and hawthorn flies

         p
         strong Other speciation Examples

         p Use these articles to supplement the examples used in the curriculum. Students can even summarize evidence on the Speciation Organizer as they read through the articles.

         ul
            li Grizzly bears and polar bears
               ul
                  li
                     a(href="http://sciencenordic.com/grizzly-polar-bear-hybrids-spotted-canadian-arctic" target="_blank") Grizzly polar bear hybrids spotted in Canadian Arctic
                     |  — a 2016 Science Nordic article by Catherine Jex
                  li
                     a(href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2016/05/23/love-in-the-time-of-climate-change-grizzlies-and-polar-bears-are-now-mating/" target="_blank") Love in the time of climate change
                     | : grizzlies and polar bears are now mating — a 2016 Washington Post article by Adam Popescu (Note that the particular bear that was hunted in May of 2016 was later found to be a
                     a(href="http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/north/blonde-grizzly-hybrid-polar-1.3645547" target="_blank") blonde grizzly
                     | , not a hybrid. However, the article also includes a lot of useful information.)
            li
               | Common and Australian blacktip sharks.
               a(href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/health-science/first-ever-hybrid-shark-discovered-off-australia/2012/01/03/gIQAPy00YP_story.html" target="_blank")  First-ever hybrid shark discovered off Australia
               |  — a 2012 Washington Post article by Juliet Eilperin
            li
               a(href="https://www.wired.com/2016/09/giraffes-get-caught-great-genetics-nerd-fight/" target="_blank") Giraffes get caught up in the great genetics nerd fight
               |  — a Wired article by Marley Walker
            li
               a(href="http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/coywolves-are-taking-over-eastern-north-america-180957141/?no-ist" target="_blank") Coywolves are taking over eastern North America
               |  — In this 2015 Smithsonian article, Marissa Fessenden describes some of the history and genetic analysis of Eastern coyotes. The article includes links to other resources.
            li
               a(href="http://therattlingcrow.blogspot.com/2014/04/summer-and-winter-blackcaps-and.html" target="_blank") Summer and winter Blackcaps and evolution
               |  — a 2014 blog entry about two Eurasian blackcap populations, with links to two primary research articles
            li
               a(href="http://phys.org/news/2016-08-soapberry-bugs-host.html" target="_blank") What happens when soapberry bugs switch to a new host?
               |  — This 2016 article on phys.org by Kathy Keatley Garvey describes how a population of soapberry bugs has moved to a new host. It's a story very similar to that of hawthorn and apple flies.
            li
               a(href="https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/see-change-rapid-emergence/" target="_blank") Sea Change
               | : Rapid emergence of new sea star species illustrates evolution's power — This 2012 Scientific American article by Marissa Fessenden describes a case of rapid speciation in an Australian starfish.
